The paper discusses evaluative bibliometrics, which involves analyzing research units using statistical procedures. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), computational complexity (cs.CY), information retrieval (cs.IR), social and information networks (cs.SI), and cryptography and security (cs.CR). However, since the paper focuses on analyzing publication and citation data, cs.DL and cs.CY are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.IR, cs.SI, and cs.CR.
